sessions.description:
I was in VivoCity for food, so I thought why not, let‚Äôs try walking on that seaside hiking trail. The view was awesome, highly recommended. A good place to view sunset. Don‚Äôt take this route at night though if you are scared of the dark.

Didn‚Äôt walk all the way to Pasir Panjang MRT where I lived because I was a bit sick on that day.

This trip was when I decided to start this walk-on-CCL project. ‚ÄúSoft-skipped‚Äù Haw Par Villa MRT however, since if I went there, I would have to walk a long detour to reach Kent Ridge MRT.

500m was spent when I walked the wrong way on Dover Road.
Went from my place of residence near Pasir Panjang MRT to the Fairprice near Labrador Park MRT to buy milk. Literally. I bought two litres of milk on this day.

Wanted to reach Caldecott MRT in this section, but a heavy rain came right when I was near Botanic Gardens MRT, so I just called it a day and went there instead. A rare time that I ended the walk when the sky was still bright.

It was honestly a very challenging section, because there wasn‚Äôt a lot of houses around and Google Maps got me inside the cemeteries here. The path Google Maps told me, by which I would reach the unconstructed Bukit Brown MRT, wasn‚Äôt even cemented, and it was already dark then, so I just went ahead and got out of the cemetery to continue on Lornie Highway.

Now thinking back, I should‚Äôve just followed Lornie Highway all the way, and I would‚Äôve got to Marymount MRT in 5km rather than Caldecott MRT in 7km.

The chicken rice at Adam Food Centre was very yummy, by the way.

First day of the new year.

Took this section before continuing from Caldecott MRT because I wanted to see the MBS Drone Show that would take place at 8pm the same day. While the sidewalk was wide, there were a lot of traffic lights and the section near MBS was expectedly incredibly crowded with tourists.

At Marina Square (Esplanade MRT ‚Äì Promenade MRT), the sidewalk seemed to not exist (?) and I somehow found myself walking inside a shopping mall like a lost man. It was hot outside and the mall was air conditioned, so it was not so bad after all.

Second day of the new year. Thankfully I still managed to find chicken rice when I passed by Bishan.

Planned to turn left to Upper Serangoon Road to get to Serangoon MRT as the destination, then take NEL to get home, but since Bartley MRT isn‚Äôt that far away, decided to continue straight ahead on Bartley Road for Bartley MRT instead.

The trip with probably one of the latest starting time and ending time in the entire project. I planned to only finish in Paya Lebar MRT but when I passed it, I thought it was still early so why not continue.

Wanted to even finish the entire CCL by going straight to Promenade MRT but it was 10:40pm when I reached Mountbatten MRT and I decided to end here because I didn‚Äôt know if I could finish the next three stations before CCL closing time.

The section from Paya Lebar MRT doesn‚Äôt follow roads but instead a park connector along Geylang River. This is part of my favourite biking path in Singapore, which goes from Paya Lebar MRT, along the left side of the river, to reach Marina Barrage and Gardens by the Bay MRT.

Rochor Road unexpectedly did not have a pedestrian path from the other side of Nicoll Highway, so had to go inside Suntec City and get lost there. The second mall in the project, the first that was intentional.

Dropped by Golden Mile Food Centre for dinner.

CCL is completed other than the CCL6 that is still under construction.

First trip on NEL. Apple Map had me walk on grass by the exit ramp of AYE for a good while. It wanted me to touch some grass maybe. Not sure if I broke any laws by walking like that, my apologises if I did.

Had dinner in Chinatown. Most food stalls are closing at 6:45pm when I was in the food court, so I decided to have Vietnamese food in the nearby Vietnamese restaurant instead. S$12.90 for a b√∫n ri√™u, crazy expensive compared to the same thing in Hanoi, but it was good and the price is expected for a Singaporean restaurant.

Wanted to reach Little India MRT via Fort Canning Park, but that was a hill üò≠ and my legs understandably protested. So ended up finishing in Dhoby Ghaut MRT instead.

That was a relatively calm walk, since the line thankfully goes pretty straight and there's road right up above so I just needed to go straight ahead without looking at my map or scrambling for pedestrian paths much.

Passed by Little India and I was amazed at how many jewellery shops there were. Like, maybe 60% of all the shops that I saw were jewellery shops, which is absolutely unreal.

Planned to end at Potong Pasir MRT since it looks like a good midpoint of the whole line (I want to do NEL in 4 sessions), but the road was not hilly and it was pretty easy, so decided to walk until CCL so I could get home without transferring trains.

The remaining section is still too long (about 8.12 km) for one single session, but the two remaining planned sessions will probably be pretty short. Or should I go wild and do the 8 km walk?

Decided to finish NEL within today. Was it a good decision? I‚Äôd say yes. But as expected it was tiring as heck. My body ran out of water to convert to sweat before I reached the interchange with TPE.

For some reasons the map tracking app stopped working midway, so the part around Hougang MRT is inaccurate. I fixed the distance count by measuring the distance on Google Maps, but the pace and calories counts are not as accurate as other sessions.

Initially planned to go through Republic Poly, but the gate was closed so I just assumed the campus wasn‚Äôt open to the public and so took the loooong detour to Admiralty Road. I think this detour made the trip at least 30% longer.

A portion of Admiralty Park being closed certainly didn‚Äôt help make the detour shorter.

I probably could have just asked a nearby student if the campus was open, then went to security to get myself the shortcut, but the trip was planned to be short anyway so the detour is fine. That said, coming to the southern gate of the polytechnic, I noticed the campus might be open to the public after all. The gates and fences were nowhere to be found, compared to the gate neat Woodlands North MRT.

The next trip is gonna be hard. The distance between Woodlands South MRT and Springleaf MRT is really long and I‚Äôm expecting myself to go deep into Ulu Sembawang Park. Any obstacles happen and I could be sent back all the way to Woodlands South MRT.

Holy cow. Well, I don‚Äôt think I will do a 10km+ session again during this project.

Initially planned to finish in Springleaf MRT, but had a good meal and two Milo‚Äôs near the station, and it was still bright then, so decided to continue to Lentor MRT. My legs were mayday‚Äôing as I went into the final kilometre.

Walking with a Protected Area (Mandai Depot) to the left and a military training area to the right was certainly fun. Thankfully I decided to start earlier than usual (thanks weather), since the park connector is not illuminated.

The view of Upper Seletar Resevoir Lake was awesome. Will come back there again. There were no water stations or vending machines nearby though which was unfortunate.

I don‚Äôt think I will have another session where I cross an expressway (SLE) three times like this one.

The burning Phuket probably affected the way my body sweats, because just 1km into the session and I was already sweating drops of water all over my face. The entire session was a lot more sweaty than average.

Thankfully my leg still remembered how to walk after the one week break, because I only needed to rest once (for that sweating, 1km in) throughout the entire session.

The stretch between Caldecott MRT and Orchard MRT, especially the stretch from Newtons MRT, is probably the richest area in Singapore. Tons of luxury hotels and apartments. And not a single food court, to the dismay of my screaming stomach.

Planned to finish at Orchard MRT, but it was still relatively early at the time, and my leg was still good, so decided to extend until Outram Park MRT.

Thankfully it didn‚Äôt rain during the entire session. The weather had been very cloudy and it looked like it could rain any time for the whole day.

Hurray, that‚Äôs TEL finished. Until a few months later when more stations are opened east of Gardens by the Bay MRT‚Ä¶

While this session was relatively short (compared to recent sessions), I was caught in the rain multiple times‚Ä¶ The session also went over downtown streets which meant traffic light junctions were everywhere, so there were a lot of breaks.

Marina Mall was closed for some construction project so there was one weird detour near the closed Marina South MRT, as I attempted to walk on that road but failed.

The pedestrian sidewalk to the south of Marina Gardens Drive was absolutely creepy. It was not illuminated, the ground was filled with fallen leaves and there were animals jumping around in the dark. The rain and my fear of snakes didn‚Äôt help at all. Ah well, I still got out of it intact.

It was a very pleasant day today. I found that in a happy day, even when Apple Weather told me there would be no rain causing me to be soaked in light rain the entire way, my mood would still not be dampened.

The track today was pretty easy, there weren‚Äôt many traffic light crossings, so I didn‚Äôt have to stop for red light a lot of times. There weren‚Äôt many turns either, so I didn‚Äôt have to stop to look at the map. I think that partially contributed to my pace today, as this is the first time I reached sub-11 pace ‚Äì my slowest kilometre is still higher than all averages of previous sessions. Wow. Not sure if I can keep up with this pace in future sessions ‚Äì to get any faster I think I would have to run rather than walk.

Former Bukit Timah Fire Station was not lighted and the buildings looked unmaintained, so in the dark it looked a bit scary. But the pedestrian sidewalk was well illuminated so it was completely fine.

So despite the rain, that was a great start for Downtown Line.

Yesterday it said no rain, didn‚Äôt bring umbrella, got soaked in rain the entire session. Today it said there would be rain, brought umbrella, not a single drop of rain appeared. Ah well‚Ä¶ The umbrella made it not so easy and comfortable anymore to swing the arms, but dropped by a 7-11 to grab two bottles of drinks (thanks, discount), drank one and used one to counter the weight of the umbrella, so it became comfortable to walk again.

Half the session I had to take detours due to the construction of the North‚ÄìSouth Corridor. Construction projects have been the number one cause of unplanned detours in this project.

Things were going well and I wanted to stop in Bayfront MRT, but somehow just when I was approaching Promenade MRT my right foot‚Äôs toes started to hurt, so decided to call it a day and stop one station early. Tomorrow I have an exam anyway, it doesn‚Äôt hurt to stop earlier than planned.

I said I would not do a 10km+ session again after the TE3‚ÄìTE5 session on TEL. Well, I just did it again!

Initially I intended to stop at Geylang Bahru MRT, but eventually decided to extend until I reached CCL. Why? I am not under time pressure today (unlike most other days when I have something to do at around 10pm), and I live near CCL.

The session was relatively uneventful, with the roads pretty easy to navigate. However I walked on the wrong side of the road on the exit ramp of PIE near Geylang Bahru MRT. So I lost about 200m there having to turn around to cross the road (you don‚Äôt want to jaywalk into vehicles travelling at expressway speed), so that I could use the pedestrian overpass crossing PIE. Lesson learned, be extra careful and never mess with expressways‚Ä¶

That 200m was won back after I found a shortcut via the HDB blocks between Mattar MRT and MacPherson MRT. Really lucky that HDB common grounds are publicly accessible. I should use this trick more.

Another relatively simple session as the line just followed a single road for almost the entire distance. I didn‚Äôt have to look at the map for directions until I was about to reach the destination (Tampines MRT). That MRT station is huge though, surprisingly big for a two-line interchange (I guess it‚Äôs due to me having to cross a bus interchange as well).

The first one third of the session, I walked alongside a Bangladeshi man. He seems frustrated with his current work and the rising cost of living. All the best to him, though I must admit I couldn‚Äôt listen to at least half of what he said because his accent was too heavy for my ears, historically scoring badly in listening tests.

Bedok Reservoir was a bit smaller than I thought. Just a lake and that‚Äôs it? Compared to the huge central reservoirs that make my legs protest before I even attempt to hike across them, this one feels too small to be given the reservoir title‚Ä¶
No comments today. Towards the end today has been terrible and I am tired.

First impression has to be that the East has a LOT of cycling paths, public space and children playground. Which seems to be partially due to the overground train viaduct, as you cannot build anything under the viaducts so you might as well make them public green space.

The porridge in Pasir Ris Central Hawker Centre is fantastic. A really good way to start the session. The hawker centre was slightly further away from the station than I would like it to, however.

Another thing I noticed is that the gap between stations is quite large. Unlike other newer lines, it takes a lot of time to go from Tanah Merah MRT to Bedok MRT. And I really should have stopped at Tanah Merah MRT. My legs are trembling as I type these lines on a train heading away from Bedok MRT.

Planned to finish at Kallang MRT, but I felt a bit sick. I also observed that even in the first kilometre, I couldn‚Äôt maintain the pace I wanted to have, and I would only become slower as I continued further. I also had to take an abnormally long break only 500m in. Considering everything, I decided to end the session VERY prematurely.

I guess, after several days of consecutive long walking sessions, my legs have reached some kind of critical points. Maybe I should take a rest for a few days before continuing again, this time perhaps aiming for City Hall MRT.
